Notes: Ferdinand was born in Vienna to the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koháry. He grew up in cosmopolitian family of European nobility with family ties to Austria-Hungary, France, Belgium, Hungary, Portugal and Britain. Primarily raised and educated in Austria and Hungary, he also frequented his family properties in Solvakia and Belgium, his wife's homeland. He and his family frequently travelled across Europe, frequently visiting Switzerland and France. Ferdinand atten the Theresian Military Academy in Vienna. In the 1880s, he served in the Austro-Hungarian Imperial Army rose to lieutenant in the Eleventh Regiment of the Austrian Hussars , and senior lieutenantof the Honvéd-Hussars in the Hungarian Cavalry on November 1, 1886. In 1887, he was offered the crown of Bulgaria, a principality that was still nominally an autonomous territory within the Ottoman Empire.
Sources: Constant, Stephen. Foxy Ferdinand, 1861-1948, Tsar of Bulgaria. Sidgwick & Jackson, 1979.

Notes: Chadian military leader and politician, was born in the village of Berdoba. His father was a poor herder who belonged to the Bidayat clan of the small Zaghawa ethnic community. He began his education at a quar?anic school in Tiné and the École Française at Fada before attending secondary school at the Lycée Franco-Arabe at Abéché, the Lycée Jacques Moudeina at Bangor. He then entered the military and graduated from an officers’ training school in the Chadian capital of N’Djamena. Like many other military officers, he then received further training to become a pilot in France in the late 1970s.

Notes: Working as a kichen hand aboard a French ship, Ho arrived in France in 1911. In 1912, Ho travlled to the US, living in New York City between 1912-13. Between 1913-19, Ho lived in West Ealing, and Crouch End, Briatin, working for a local hotels. 1919-23, Ho moved to Paris. He petitioned the Paris Peace Confernece for Vietnamese self-determination. He also became a activist in the French socialist movement. In 1923, Ho went to Mosocow, to join the Comintern, stuyding at the Communist University of the Toilers of the East. In 1924, He travled to Guangzhou, China, joining the Chinese Military Academy at Whampoa as a instructer. After Chiang Kai-Shek's anti-Communist coup in 1927, Ho left China, traveling to Russia, Belgium, Germany, Switzerland, Italy, and Thailand. In 1930, He moved to Hong Kong to organize Vietnamese communist party and got arrested for it. He eventually got released and went to study at the Lenin Institute in Moscow. In 1938, Ho returned to China as an adviser to the Chinese communist in south-west China. After the Japanese occupation of Indochina, Ho retuned to Vietnam in 1941 to organize armed resistance.
Sources: William J. Duiker. Ho Chi Minh: A Life. New York: Hyperion, 2001

Notes: Originally exiled after Jambelí Navel force in 1865 to Panama and Colombia until 1875. He left again to Panama in 1878 tofight against Veintemilla's Revolution. He was imprisoned and until 1879. He returned again 1882 to continue fighting, went into exile again and toured around Latin America for some years through Costa Rica and Nicaragua as well. He returned and was made a najor general in Ecuadorian Army in 1895. He left office by a coup in 1911 and went to exile in Chile. Notes: He moved to Paris in 1844 as an 11 year old to study at Lycée Henri IV. He returned in 1845 after his family's economic security was lost in the Revolution of March 6, 1845. He moved to Chile in 1847. His love poem to Carolina Lizardi allegedly in indirectly caused her to commit suicide. In 1855 he returned to study law in Lima. He was sent in 1861 to France as plenipotentiary minister of Ecuador. He was also appointed Minister of Business in France in order to speed up the process of making Ecuador a French protectorate. He traveled to England in 1971 for economic negotiations. In 1873 he went to the US. He was imprisoned by Veintemilla in 1877 and left for New York in 1878 where he stayed until 1883. In 1892 he moved to France and never returned to Ecuador. He died in Switzerland and his body was originally buried in Père-Lachaise Cemetery.

Notes: Originally exiled after Jambelí Navel force in 1865 to Panama and Colombia until 1875. He left again to Panama in 1878 tofight against Veintemilla's Revolution. He was imprisoned and until 1879. He returned again 1882 to continue fighting, went into exile again and toured around Latin America for some years through Costa Rica and Nicaragua as well. He returned and was made a najor general in Ecuadorian Army in 1895. He left office by a coup in 1911 and went to exile in Chile. He was later imprisoned by political enemies and brutally killed and mutilated by an anti-liberal lynch mob that attacked him and other political prisoners while in their cells.

Notes: From 1887 (age 20) to 1889, Mannerheim attended the Nicholas Cavalry College in St. Petersburg.In January 1891, he joined the Chevalier Guard Regiment in St Petersburg. He served in the unit until 1904. During the Russo-Japanese war he fought in Manchuria. in 1906, Disguised as an ethnographic collector, he joined the French archeologist Paul Pelliot's expedition at Samarkand in Russian Turkestan (now Uzbekistan) and travelled across much of Central Asia as well the Chinese Northwest, including Xinjiang, Gansu, Shannxi, eventually reaching Beijing. In July 1908, he travelled to Japan and returned to St. Petersberg by sea. During WWI, he fought in Poland. He returned to Finland in November 1917.
Sources: Meri, Veijo (1990). Suomen marsalkka C. G. Mannerheim.p.129.Tamm, Eric Enno. The Horse That Leaps Through Clouds: A Tale of Espionage, the Silk Road and the Rise of Modern China. Douglas & McIntyre, 2010.

Notes: Mussolini moved to Switzerland to avoid military servcie. He worked as a stonemason in various of Swiss cities including Geneva, Fribourg and Bern. He became a activist in the Italian socialist organization and labor movement in Switzerland for which he was arrested and deported in 1903. In 1904, he studied social sciences at the University of Lausanne. As he was convicted for avoding conscription, he was froced into exile in Switzerland until an amensty was announced that would allow him to return to Italy on the condition of completing military service. In 1909, he worked in a labor organization in to Trento, in Austria-Hungary. In 1915-1917, he fought on the Isonzo front in modern day Slovenia
Sources: Bosworth, Richard JB. Mussolini. Bloomsbury Publishing, 2014.

Notes: Rainilaiarivony studied from a school opened by the London Missionary Society (LMS) for the children of the noble class in the royal palace of Antananarivo. He then served as a political advisor and military commander-in-chief to suppress the rebellion in the country. After a coup d'état against the overly conservative policies of the current king, he led the country's accelerated modernization with the creation of eight cabinets: foreign affairs, interior, education, war, justice, commerce and industry, finance, and legislation. There was also the modernization of the army with the assistance of a British military instructor, who was hired to recruit, train and manage soldiers. The expansion of the public education system and the enactment of the Compulsory School Attendance Act, the opening of the first hospital three years later, and the reduction in the number of death sentences by improving laws and regulations to create a humanitarian society during his administration. External relations: had good relations with Britain and a large number of British missionaries, military advisors and diplomats, actively pursued international interests and prevented the French colonial strategy towards Madagascar. 1883, the French invaded Madagascar and lost the war, Rainilaiarivony was exiled and eventually died in Algeria.

Notes: Hastings Banda grew up traveling among various writers in Africa. He began his studies in Zimbabwe with his uncle before moving to South Africa for his bachelor's degree while working in the deep mines. While in South Africa, he met African Methodist Episcopal Bishop William Tecumseh Vernon, who offered to sponsor him to study at the Methodist Episcopal School in the United States. Upon arrival in the United States, he studied at the Upper School of Wilberforce College at Central State University before transferring to the University of Chicago for a B.A. in Philosophy and Meharry Medical College in Tennessee where he received his M.D. degree in Medicine. After his studies in the United States, he went to England to study for a second medical degree, which he received from the University of Edinburgh, and declined a call-up to the Army at the time while attending a course in Liverpool. He also represented Nyasaland at the British African Congress, after which he returned to live in Ghana, West Africa, and then became a leader in Malawi's independence. After becoming leader of Malawi, he practiced one-party rule (anti-communism). He was eventually overthrown due to a long period of oppressive rule.
Sources: "Man in the News; Cosmopolitan Malawian; Hastings Kamuzu Banda". The New York Times. 9 September 1964.

Notes: Studied at the University of San Francisco the last year of secondary school through the US Peace Corps and went on to study there. He got two masters at Stanford in 1972. He served as a consultant for the Stanford Research Institute. In 1975 he moved to Paris for the OECD. In 1978 he worked at the Inter-American Bank in DC as well as worked as an associate professor of Econ at American University. Then he worked for the World Bank. In 1989 he was the leader of UNDP and ILO in New York. He was a fellow at Harvard from 1991-4. During the same time he was a visiting professor at the Waseda University in Tokyo, Japan. He got a PhD in economics of HR at Stanford in 1993. After his presidency he returned to the US to work at Stanford. He married the same woman twice. His presidency was embroiled in several scandals including affairs and illegitimate children. He was arrested in the US in 2019 to be extradited to Peru but given bail in 2020 .

Notes: Between 1895-1898, Hoover was hired by Bewick, Moreing & Co., a British company that operated gold mines in Western Australia and Southern Australia. Hoover left Bewick, to operate as a independent mining consultant and financier in London before the Great War. After the outbreak of the Great War, Hoover operated the American relief mission from London. In terms of travel, Hoover worked with mining firms in Russia and British Burma during his consultant years he has also attended the Paris Peace Conference as a adviser to President Wilson.

Notes: Ford served on aircraft carreier USS Monterey in th Pacific in 1943-44, fighting in the southwest pacific and participated in the battle for the Philippines. According to himself, Ford has been a "American First" isolationist prior to the Second World War. But experience aboard converted him into an internationalist. 1943-44, Ford is assigned to sea duty aboard the carrier USS Monterey as the ship’s athletic officer and one of the ship’s gunnery officers. He sees action in the Pacific Theater aboard the USS Monterey in the Battle of Makin. The ship also takes part in attacks against Kwajalein and Eniwetok, New Guinea, Saipan, Guam, and Formosa. He also survives a typhoon in the Pacific that batters the Monterey on December 18, 1944.
Sources: Kunhardt Jr., Phillip (1999). Gerald R. Ford "Healing the Nation". New York: Riverhead Books. pp. 79–85. ;Cannon, James. Gerald R. Ford: An Honorable Life. University of Michigan Press, 2013.

Notes: Jimmy Carter, served aboard the submarine USS Pomfret from 17 December 1948 to 1 February 1951 as his first shipboard assignment. Though the submarine operates in East Asia and was based in Qingdao, China, the USS Pomfret was based in Pearl Harbor during Carter's service. So Carter did not serve in China despite receiving a "China Service Medal". In 1952 Carter was sent to Chalk River Laboratories in Canada as part of a US navy maintainance team aftera a nuclear meltdown at the facility. According to Carter, this experience shaped his view towards the danger of atomic energy, and his decision to stop the neutron weapon development when he was the president.
Sources: Bourne, Peter G. Jimmy Carter: a comprehensive biography from plains to post-presidency. Scribner Book Company, 1997.

Notes: Tito was born in Kumrovec, on the modern day Croatian-Slovenian border. He was of Croat-Slovene background and spoke Slovene in school. i 1912, he worked in a afactory in Cenkov and Plzen, Bohemia. Subsequently, he moved to Munich, a Mannheim, and the Ruhr, and Vienna working for different manufacturing companies including Mercedes-Benz. During the first world war, he fought in a Croatian unit in the Austro-Hungarian Army. He was sent to have military training in Budapest. During the war, he fough in Serbia, Poland and Western Ukraine. He was captured by the Russian forces on the eastern front and sent to POW camps in European Russia and  Siberia. In 1934, he fled into exile in the Soviet Union. During the Spanish civil  war, Tito was in France, oragnizing communist volunteers to fight for the Spanish Republic.

Notes: Ian Smith is a Rhodesian politician (formerly of Zimbabwe). Grew up in Zimbabwe, but his father was a first generation immigrant from Scotland. Smith went to university in Cape Town, South Africa as an adult due to his excellent physical attributes, and then the Second World War began. Smith was forced to join the war because Rhodesia was a British colony, and before he finished college he volunteered to enlist in the British Army to complete flight training and join the 237th Squadron of the Royal Air Force. After the war, he lived in the United States and South Africa, and married in 1948. After he became prime minister, he banned nationalist organizations in Zimbabwe, and eventually declared independence unilaterally after he became too radical and targeted. Later in his political career, Smith was too conservative and tended to favor white interests, and he opposed any propagation of communist ideas within Zimbabwe.
Sources: Berlyn 1978.

Notes:
Robert Mugabe was born early in life to a Catholic family in Zimbabwe and spent his adult life studying history and English literature at the University of South Africa at Fort Hare in South Africa. He also attended the University of Fort Hare in South Africa. He also remotely earned a bachelor's degree in management from the University of London's International Program. During his eight years of incarceration from 1963-1975, he earned several degrees from the University of London while in prison: a master's degree in economics, a bachelor's degree in management and two law degrees.
While at university, he learned about Marxism and was arrested for his personal African nationalism, which called for the creation of a black African nation. After his release, he founded the Zimbabwe African National Union to fight against the white government, a war known as the Rhodesian Bush War. The war culminated in peace talks and democratic elections in 1980, which Mugabe won. His desire to build a socialist state led him to suppress white immigration during his administration, which led to a deterioration in social relations. He also participated in the Second Congo War and organized the Organization of African Unity, the African Union, the Non-Aligned Movement, and others. He aspired to pursue decolonization. He continued to rule Zimbabwe until the coup d'état.
He went into exile in Mozambique to organize guerrila war in 1975.
Sources: Blair 2002, p. 22; Meredith 2002, p. 34.
